ity: Syrian migrants' legal status, the spaces in which they live and work, and their movements within and outside Turkey. The difficulties they face include restricted access to education and healthcare, struggles to secure employment, language barriers, identity-based discrimination, and unlawful deportations. Feyzi Baban, Suzan Ilcan, and Kim Rygiel show that Syrians confront their precarious conditions by engaging in cultural production and community-building activities, and by undertaking perilous journeys to Europe, allowing them to claim spaces and citizenship while asserting their rights to belong, to stay, and to escape. The authors draw on migration policies, legal and scholarly materials, and five years of extensive field research with local, national, and international humanitarian organizations, and with Syrians from all walks of life.The Precarious Lives of Syrians offers a thoughtful and compelling analysis of migration precarity in our contemporary context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aRefugeesxGovernment policyzTurkey. 0aRefugeesxLegal status, laws, etczTurkey. 0aSyrianszTurkeyxEconomic conditions. 0aSyrianszTurkeyxSocial conditions. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Immigration.2bisacsh  aEU Turkey Statement.  aSyrian refugees in Middle East.  aSyrian refugees in Turkey.  aSyrian refugees.  adisplaced persons.  adisplaced populations.  ahuman displacement.  ahumanitarian aid refugees.  ahumanitarian organizations.  ainternational migrants.  arefugee journeys.  atemporary protection.1 aAlmustafa, Maissaa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIlcan, Suzan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRygiel, Kim, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dD